The '''373rd (Croatian) Infantry Division''' ({{lang-de|373. (Kroatische) Infanterie-Division}}, {{lang-hr|373. (hrvatska) pješačka divizija}}) was a [[Division (military)|division]] of the [[German Army (Wehrmacht)|German Army]] during [[World War II]]. It was formed in June 1943 using a brigade from the [[Croatian Home Guard (Independent State of Croatia)|Home Guard]] of the [[Independent State of Croatia]] ({{lang-hr|Nezavisna Država Hrvatska|links=no}}, NDH) with the addition of a German [[en cadre|cadre]]. The division was commanded by Germans down to [[battalion]] and even [[Company (military unit)|company]] level in nearly all cases, and was commonly referred to as a "legionnaire division". Originally formed with the intention of service on the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]], it was used instead for anti-[[Yugoslav Partisan|Partisan]] operations in the territory of the NDH until the end of the war. It fought mainly in the western areas of the NDH, and was involved in the [[Operation Rösselsprung (1944)|attempt to kill or capture the leader of the Partisans]], [[Josip Broz Tito]], in May 1944. Severely depleted by desertion, the division withdrew towards the [[Nazi Germany|Reich]] border in the early months of 1945, eventually surrendering to the Partisans on 10 May 1945 near [[Brežice]] in modern-day [[Slovenia]].

==History==

===Formation===
After the [[Axis Powers|Axis]] [[Operation Barbarossa|invasion of the Soviet Union]] in June 1941, [[Ante Pavelić]], the leader of the newly created Axis [[puppet state]] the [[Independent State of Croatia]] (NDH), offered [[Adolf Hitler]] volunteers to serve on the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]]. This offer soon resulted in the formation and deployment of army, air force and naval detachments which, after being trained and equipped by Germany, were committed to fighting the [[Red Army]]. The largest element was the [[369th Croatian Reinforced Infantry Regiment (Wehrmacht)|369th Croatian Reinforced Infantry Regiment]], which was part of the [[100th Light Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|100th Jäger Division]], but was decimated at [[Stalingrad]] in January 1943. The Croatian forces performed creditably on the Eastern Front, and the Germans continued to support the development of NDH forces with the aim of raising several divisions to serve there. Due to the lack of trained leaders and staff, these divisions were raised using a German [[en cadre|cadre]].{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|pp=266–267}}

The 373rd (Croatian) Infantry Division was assembled and trained in [[Stockerau]] and [[Döllersheim]], [[Austria in the time of National Socialism|Austria]], commencing from the end of January 1943 as the second Croatian division raised for service in the [[Wehrmacht]], following its sister formation, the [[369th (Croatian) Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|369th (Croatian) Infantry Division]].{{sfn|Schraml|1962|p=155}} It was built around a cadre of 3,500 German troops, and 8,500 soldiers of the 7th Mountain Brigade of the [[Croatian Home Guard (Independent State of Croatia)|Croatian Home Guard]], the regular army of the NDH.{{sfn|Nafziger|2000|p=322}}{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|pp=267–268}} It was established with two infantry [[regiment]]s of three battalions each. Each regiment was allocated the manpower from two of the four battalions of the 7th Mountain Brigade.{{sfn|Nafziger|1993|p=1–2}} It was formed under the command of ''[[Generalmajor]]'' (Brigadier) [[Emil Zellner]],{{sfn|Nafziger|2000|p=322}} with the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross]] recipient ''[[Oberst]]'' (Colonel) [[Alois Windisch]] commanding the 383rd (Croatian) Grenadier Regiment and ''Oberst'' Boicetta commanding the 384th (Croatian) Grenadier Regiment.{{sfn|Schraml|1962|p=155}} All battalions were commanded by Germans except for the reconnaissance battalion, which was commanded by a Croat officer, Major Bakarec.{{sfn|Schraml|1962|p=156}} The Croatian divisions that served in the Wehrmacht were commonly known as "legionnaire divisions".{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=267}}

Although originally intended for use on the Eastern Front, the division did not deploy there and returned to the NDH in May 1943 due to the need to combat the [[League of Communists|communist]]-led [[Yugoslav Partisans|Partisans]] in the territory of the NDH.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=267}} The division left its training area in Austria over the period 1–12 May 1943, travelling by train via the route [[Vienna]]–[[Graz]]–[[Maribor|Marburg]]–[[Zagreb]].{{sfn|Schraml|1962|p=156}} It was known as the "Tiger Division" ({{lang-hr|Tigar Divizija}}),{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=267}} and was subordinated to the [[Croatia Command (Wehrmacht)|Croatia Command]] ({{lang-de|Befehlshaber Kroatien}}) of ''[[General of the Infantry (Germany)|General der Infanterie]]'' (Lieutenant General) [[Rudolf Lüters]].{{sfn|Bishop|2008|p=56}}

